The probability of visiting a physical therapist $P(P)$ and a chiropractor $P(C)$ can be determined using the principle of inclusion-exclusion for probabilities:
$P(P \cup C) = P(P) + P(C) - P(P \cap C)$

Given:
1.  The probability of visiting neither is $8\%$, so $P((P \cup C)^c) = 0.08$. This means $P(P \cup C) = 1 - 0.08 = 0.92$.
2.  The probability of visiting both is $28\%$, so $P(P \cap C) = 0.28$.
3.  The probability of visiting a physical therapist exceeds the probability of visiting a chiropractor by $16\%$, so $P(P) = P(C) + 0.16$.

Substituting these into the inclusion-exclusion formula:
$0.92 = P(P) + P(C) - 0.28$
$0.92 + 0.28 = P(P) + P(C)$
$1.20 = P(P) + P(C)$

Now substitute $P(C) = P(P) - 0.16$ into the equation:
$1.20 = P(P) + (P(P) - 0.16)$
$1.20 = 2P(P) - 0.16$
$1.36 = 2P(P)$
$P(P) = \frac{1.36}{2} = 0.68$

The probability of a randomly selected person visiting a physical therapist is $0.68$ (or $68\%$).

The final answer is $0.68$
